d2628d69-a82f-4073-b35d-200fdec46ee1.title: The Great Houses
d2628d69-a82f-4073-b35d-200fdec46ee1.content:
What started as internet money - an asset that cannot be duplicated - quickly spiraled out into all kinds of assets.

One of the first assets was a stablecoin. As crypto currencies are known to be volatile in value, people figured it would make sense to have coins whose value is stable.

This is essentially done by locking up your volatile crypto (Ether) to mint some of the stable-value coin. If the value of your Ether gets close to the value of your Dai, your Ether gets liquidated (sold).

Soon, people were locking up Ether (volatile) to borrow Dai (stable) & locking up Dai to borrow Ether, based on whether they thought the value of Ether would go up or down.

To create a supply of tokens big enough for people to take out loans, lending protocols started incentivizing people to become liquidity providers & borrow their crypto to others, for a small fee & governance tokens of the said protocol.

Cutting out the middleman that is the bank, people lending directly to each other & no more shadow banking bullshit.

This was the birth of Decentralized Finance aka DeFi.

Fortunes were made & lost in the DeFi summer of 2020...

2c71bb8e-b8c9-4638-9112-375d38913c9e.content:
The next big thing was Ethereum.

A programmable decentralized accounting system.

This opened a world of opportunities.

It allowed people to start building applications, program value flows & create all kinds of digital assets all secured by a blockchain.

This all sounds a bit abstract but there's a world of difference between applications running on a blockchain vs applications running on centralized databases.

Besides being less fragile, service providers (creators of applications) are, in theory, be able to guarantee what happens because things in this magical database can only be changed according to pre-set rules written in "smart contracts" that are visible for anyone to read & verify on their own.

Of course, this all turned out much harder & dangerous in practice.

But it also opened a world of possibilities, without even getting into the benefits of all applications running on a single decentralized database rather than walled gardens...
